We know how to differentiate a thing

297
00:11:34,220 --> 00:11:35,160
with lower indices.

298
00:11:36,580 --> 00:11:37,720
That's this formula

299
00:11:39,040 --> 00:11:40,080
over here.

300
00:11:40,760 --> 00:11:42,740
If you just plug that in here,

301
00:11:42,740 --> 00:11:44,720
and manipulate it a little bit,

302
00:11:44,940 --> 00:11:47,820
you'll find out how to differentiate,

303
00:11:48,120 --> 00:11:49,520
how to covariantly differentiate

304
00:11:49,520 --> 00:11:51,440
a tensor with upper indices.

305
00:11:51,920 --> 00:11:53,560
I'll write the formula for you.

306
00:11:54,840 --> 00:11:55,740
Here it is.

307
00:11:55,860 --> 00:11:57,360
It's the same kind of thing

308
00:11:57,360 --> 00:11:58,600
as up here.

309
00:12:00,360 --> 00:12:01,920
Derivative with respect to m

310
00:12:01,920 --> 00:12:03,620
of vn,

311
00:12:04,459 --> 00:12:06,240
derivative with respect to xm

312
00:12:06,240 --> 00:12:07,800
of vn,

313
00:12:07,860 --> 00:12:09,520
they always start out that way,

314
00:12:09,640 --> 00:12:10,760
and then,

315
00:12:10,760 --> 00:12:11,140
now,

316
00:12:11,140 --> 00:12:11,780
plus,

317
00:12:11,780 --> 00:12:13,840
this you'll work out by doing

318
00:12:13,840 --> 00:12:15,100
this little exercise here.

319
00:12:15,540 --> 00:12:16,880
It's a simple little exercise,

320
00:12:17,080 --> 00:12:17,780
takes a few minutes.

321
00:12:18,640 --> 00:12:19,740
And now it's plus

322
00:12:21,900 --> 00:12:22,700
gamma m

323
00:12:24,020 --> 00:12:24,420
n,

324
00:12:25,620 --> 00:12:26,580
let's call it,

325
00:12:27,180 --> 00:12:27,580
p,

326
00:12:27,580 --> 00:12:28,160
I guess,

327
00:12:28,160 --> 00:12:28,900
what did I call it?

328
00:12:28,960 --> 00:12:30,580
I'd like to keep my notation consistent.

329
00:12:31,620 --> 00:12:32,020
nmr,

330
00:12:32,600 --> 00:12:33,000
no,

331
00:12:34,100 --> 00:12:34,500
yeah,

332
00:12:34,500 --> 00:12:34,760
r,

333
00:12:38,840 --> 00:12:39,240
vr.

334
00:12:39,819 --> 00:12:40,300
Okay,

335
00:12:40,300 --> 00:12:41,920
let's look at it for a minute.

336
00:12:43,540 --> 00:12:44,380
As before,

337
00:12:44,380 --> 00:12:46,640
it begins with just a simple derivative.

338
00:12:47,300 --> 00:12:48,580
Then it has a term

339
00:12:48,580 --> 00:12:51,280
which would be zero in the best coordinates,

340
00:12:51,380 --> 00:12:52,440
because in the best coordinates,

341
00:12:52,880 --> 00:12:53,940
the gammas are all zero.

342
00:12:54,600 --> 00:12:55,560
This would be zero,

343
00:12:55,560 --> 00:12:56,340
but it's not zero

344
00:12:56,340 --> 00:12:57,620
in general coordinates.

345
00:12:58,400 --> 00:13:00,080
This has one lower index,

346
00:13:00,380 --> 00:13:01,620
one lower index here.

347
00:13:02,040 --> 00:13:04,360
It has one upper index,

348
00:13:04,580 --> 00:13:06,400
has the same upper index here.

349
00:13:07,040 --> 00:13:08,600
Here it has a lower index,

350
00:13:08,600 --> 00:13:10,460
contracted with an upper index.

351
00:13:10,740 --> 00:13:12,500
So the formula makes sense.

352
00:13:12,640 --> 00:13:14,160
It satisfies the rules.

353
00:13:14,480 --> 00:13:16,960
Upper indices contracted with lower indices,

354
00:13:17,300 --> 00:13:18,040
summed over,

355
00:13:19,219 --> 00:13:21,440
and indices generally in place.

356
00:13:22,460 --> 00:13:23,300
It's plus.

357
00:13:23,720 --> 00:13:24,580
It's plus.

358
00:13:25,560 --> 00:13:26,320
It's plus.

359
00:13:26,640 --> 00:13:28,760
That's the little peculiarity

360
00:13:29,420 --> 00:13:31,900
that you get by doing this exercise.

361
00:13:33,140 --> 00:13:33,960
It's plus.

362
00:13:36,220 --> 00:13:37,760
That's all you really have to remember,

363
00:13:37,760 --> 00:13:40,220
that when you go from covariant to contravariant,

364
00:13:40,220 --> 00:13:42,540
the way the indices fit together,

365
00:13:42,740 --> 00:13:44,100
you can't mistake it.

366
00:13:44,400 --> 00:13:45,980
A lower index and an upper index.

367
00:13:46,280 --> 00:13:48,760
That same lower index has to appear on this side.

368
00:13:50,700 --> 00:13:52,180
There's nothing else it can be

369
00:13:52,180 --> 00:13:54,360
but the lower index of the Christoffel symbol.

370
00:13:54,700 --> 00:13:56,880
The upper index has to appear here,

371
00:13:57,040 --> 00:13:59,460
and then there has to be a contraction.

372
00:13:59,940 --> 00:14:00,480
Okay,

373
00:14:00,480 --> 00:14:03,100
that's the covariant derivative

374
00:14:03,760 --> 00:14:07,040
of the contravariant components of a tensor.

375
00:14:11,939 --> 00:14:12,380
Good.

376
00:14:12,840 --> 00:14:15,940
Now we come to an idea called parallel transport.

377
00:14:16,260 --> 00:14:18,340
We've already more or less spoken about it,

378
00:14:18,380 --> 00:14:19,880
but let's spell it out in detail.

379
00:14:30,560 --> 00:14:31,940
Supposing you have a curved space.

380
00:14:33,820 --> 00:14:34,260
Oh,

381
00:14:34,260 --> 00:14:35,740
I should write down one more thing,

382
00:14:35,860 --> 00:14:37,740
just to write it down for now.

383
00:14:38,599 --> 00:14:39,960
The curvature tensor.

384
00:14:40,100 --> 00:14:40,740
I think I won't.

385
00:14:40,740 --> 00:14:42,140
We won't need it too much tonight.

386
00:14:42,360 --> 00:14:43,500
We won't need it too much tonight.

387
00:14:43,740 --> 00:14:44,260
All right.

388
00:14:44,320 --> 00:14:46,620
And now we have some vector field.

389
00:14:46,840 --> 00:14:51,440
Let it be a vector field living on the space.

390
00:14:52,480 --> 00:14:55,260
And I'm interested in knowing whether I,

391
00:14:55,300 --> 00:14:57,000
when I move along here,

392
00:14:57,579 --> 00:15:00,400
whether the field stays parallel to itself,

393
00:15:00,620 --> 00:15:03,160
whether the vector field stays parallel to itself.

394
00:15:04,060 --> 00:15:04,700
All right,

395
00:15:04,700 --> 00:15:06,460
so I have some vector at each point here.

396
00:15:06,860 --> 00:15:07,740
At each point,

397
00:15:07,740 --> 00:15:07,740
I have a vector.

398
00:15:07,740 --> 00:15:08,560
At each point along the curve,

399
00:15:08,820 --> 00:15:10,360
and I want to know whether

400
00:15:10,360 --> 00:15:11,900
the field stays parallel to itself.

401
00:15:12,160 --> 00:15:12,480
All right.

402
00:15:13,020 --> 00:15:17,160
Parallel to itself means that the covariant derivative

403
00:15:17,160 --> 00:15:18,800
is zero along that direction.

404
00:15:19,100 --> 00:15:20,160
That's what it means.

405
00:15:20,880 --> 00:15:25,220
Covariant derivative is the difference between the vectors

406
00:15:25,520 --> 00:15:27,940
except written in the best coordinates.

407
00:15:28,400 --> 00:15:30,070
If the derivative of a vector

408
00:15:30,070 --> 00:15:31,740
from one point to another is zero,

409
00:15:31,940 --> 00:15:35,020
that vector is maintaining a relationship

410
00:15:35,020 --> 00:15:36,680
of being parallel to itself

411
00:15:38,319 --> 00:15:38,800
and the vector field is not.

412
00:15:38,940 --> 00:15:40,200
So that's actually a definition.

413
00:15:42,939 --> 00:15:43,980
But let's see.

414
00:15:44,100 --> 00:15:45,020
We have written down,

415
00:15:45,160 --> 00:15:47,300
I'm going to write down again the covariant derivative

416
00:15:47,300 --> 00:15:48,300
because we're going to use it.

417
00:15:50,460 --> 00:15:50,940
DMVN.

418
00:15:51,420 --> 00:15:53,060
Let's write that down for the moment.

419
00:15:53,460 --> 00:15:57,620
Is equal to partial of VN with respect to XM.

420
00:15:57,740 --> 00:15:58,920
I'm going to write it down again.

421
00:15:59,400 --> 00:16:03,120
Plus gamma N MR VR.

422
00:16:03,440 --> 00:16:03,840
Okay.

423
00:16:03,840 --> 00:16:05,720
That's the covariant derivative.

424
00:16:06,480 --> 00:16:07,340
Now,

425
00:16:07,340 --> 00:16:10,860
I want to consider the derivative

426
00:16:10,860 --> 00:16:13,200
along the trajectory here,

427
00:16:13,280 --> 00:16:14,900
or along this curve.

428
00:16:15,610 --> 00:16:18,020
How the vector changes from point to point.

429
00:16:18,500 --> 00:16:22,260
That simply corresponds to taking the covariant derivative,

430
00:16:24,880 --> 00:16:25,740
VN,

431
00:16:26,020 --> 00:16:30,680
and multiplying it between these two points by DX.

432
00:16:32,240 --> 00:16:33,240
Let's see.

433
00:16:34,020 --> 00:16:34,660
DXM.

434
00:16:36,020 --> 00:16:38,960
If I differentiate with respect to XM

435
00:16:38,960 --> 00:16:42,380
and then multiply by DXM,

436
00:16:43,920 --> 00:16:45,620
that can just be called

437
00:16:45,620 --> 00:16:47,420
the small change in the

438
00:16:47,420 --> 00:16:49,220
vector going from point to point

439
00:16:50,380 --> 00:16:51,320
from DX,

440
00:16:51,939 --> 00:16:54,509
except keeping track of the fact

441
00:16:54,509 --> 00:16:57,080
that the coordinates themselves may bend

442
00:16:57,080 --> 00:16:58,440
as you go from point to point.

443
00:16:58,580 --> 00:17:00,960
And that's why you have to use the covariant derivative.

444
00:17:01,440 --> 00:17:03,220
This is the change in the vector,

445
00:17:03,220 --> 00:17:04,099
V,

446
00:17:04,619 --> 00:17:06,780
in going from one point to its neighbor.

447
00:17:06,980 --> 00:17:07,900
What is it equal to?

448
00:17:08,040 --> 00:17:08,920
Let's just call it,

449
00:17:08,960 --> 00:17:09,680
let's just give it a name.

450
00:17:11,480 --> 00:17:12,000
DVN.

451
00:17:13,839 --> 00:17:15,839
It's a small change in the vector

452
00:17:15,839 --> 00:17:18,839
going from one point to a neighboring point.

453
00:17:20,500 --> 00:17:21,540
More precisely,

454
00:17:21,800 --> 00:17:23,470
it's the small change in

455
00:17:23,470 --> 00:17:25,140
the vector in the best coordinates.

456
00:17:26,180 --> 00:17:26,700
Okay.

457
00:17:26,700 --> 00:17:27,160
That's it.

458
00:17:27,220 --> 00:17:27,460
Now,

459
00:17:27,460 --> 00:17:28,319
what is that equal to?

460
00:17:28,460 --> 00:17:29,320
It's equal to

461
00:17:30,580 --> 00:17:32,220
DVN by DXM,

462
00:17:32,220 --> 00:17:34,680
times DXM.

463
00:17:34,920 --> 00:17:36,760
I'm simply multiplying this equation

464
00:17:36,760 --> 00:17:38,460
by DXM,

465
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:39,980
and then plus

466
00:17:41,720 --> 00:17:43,240
gamma MRN

467
00:17:43,240 --> 00:17:46,860
VR DXM.

468
00:17:47,100 --> 00:17:50,460
I did nothing here except multiply this by DXM

469
00:17:50,460 --> 00:17:52,620
and then sum over M.

470
00:17:54,300 --> 00:17:57,080
So let's erase the middle expression here.

471
00:17:59,840 --> 00:18:02,020
This is the covariant change

472
00:18:02,220 --> 00:18:05,020
in a vector going from one point to another.

473
00:18:05,300 --> 00:18:05,900
Now,

474
00:18:05,900 --> 00:18:07,140
this thing here,

475
00:18:07,300 --> 00:18:07,880
that's simple.

476
00:18:08,020 --> 00:18:10,780
That's just the derivative of something with respect to X

477
00:18:10,780 --> 00:18:11,520
times DX.

478
00:18:12,180 --> 00:18:13,700
That can just be called

479
00:18:14,040 --> 00:18:15,460
the differential change

480
00:18:16,240 --> 00:18:16,960
in V.

481
00:18:18,560 --> 00:18:20,680
That's the differential change in V.

482
00:18:22,400 --> 00:18:23,560
So look at this equation.

483
00:18:23,740 --> 00:18:26,520
The covariant differential change in V

484
00:18:27,180 --> 00:18:29,080
is the ordinary change in V

485
00:18:29,080 --> 00:18:31,660
plus this Christoffel symbol,

486
00:18:31,660 --> 00:18:33,200
multiplied by DX.

487
00:18:35,080 --> 00:18:37,480
This is the formula which tells you

488
00:18:37,480 --> 00:18:41,060
how a vector changes from point to point.

489
00:18:42,019 --> 00:18:42,659
Now,

490
00:18:42,659 --> 00:18:43,960
supposing I'm interested

491
00:18:44,660 --> 00:18:45,460
in defining

492
00:18:47,519 --> 00:18:50,260
a vector which is parallel to itself

493
00:18:50,260 --> 00:18:51,720
as I move along this curve.

494
00:18:52,660 --> 00:18:54,880
Parallel to itself means it doesn't change

495
00:18:54,880 --> 00:18:55,980
as you move along here.

496
00:18:57,220 --> 00:18:58,460
At each point,

497
00:18:58,660 --> 00:19:00,960
you erect some best coordinates,

498
00:19:01,660 --> 00:19:02,780
in those coordinates,

499
00:19:02,920 --> 00:19:04,720
you test whether the vector is changing.

500
00:19:05,180 --> 00:19:06,100
If not,

501
00:19:06,100 --> 00:19:06,640
you say,

502
00:19:06,700 --> 00:19:06,960
all right,

503
00:19:06,960 --> 00:19:07,120
good,

504
00:19:07,200 --> 00:19:09,540
the vector is constant along a little segment there.

505
00:19:09,720 --> 00:19:11,140
Go to the next segment.

506
00:19:11,580 --> 00:19:14,100
Erect best coordinates at that point.

507
00:19:14,240 --> 00:19:15,200
Do the same thing.

508
00:19:15,640 --> 00:19:17,220
If at every point,

509
00:19:18,320 --> 00:19:20,660
the change in the vector is zero,

510
00:19:22,420 --> 00:19:23,820
if this equals zero,

511
00:19:24,840 --> 00:19:26,840
the vector is said to be

512
00:19:27,420 --> 00:19:30,080
parallel to itself along that curve.

513
00:19:31,020 --> 00:19:33,760
As you move along that specific curve,

514
00:19:34,360 --> 00:19:38,380
the vector maintains a relationship

515
00:19:38,380 --> 00:19:40,780
of being parallel to itself.

516
00:19:41,200 --> 00:19:44,600
The best coordinates are always parallel to themselves?

517
00:19:45,160 --> 00:19:45,820
Are always what?

518
00:19:46,060 --> 00:19:47,220
Parallel to themselves?

519
00:19:47,260 --> 00:19:47,360
No,

520
00:19:47,360 --> 00:19:47,900
not necessarily.

521
00:19:48,300 --> 00:19:50,420
Once you find the best set of coordinates,

522
00:19:50,780 --> 00:19:51,920
you can rotate it.

523
00:19:52,760 --> 00:19:53,360
No,

524
00:19:53,360 --> 00:19:55,480
they don't have to be parallel to the curve,

525
00:19:56,300 --> 00:19:58,540
but they have to be fixed and well-defined.

526
00:19:58,700 --> 00:20:00,060
But they could be parallel to the curve.

527
00:20:00,080 --> 00:20:02,460
The best coordinates are not unique.

528
00:20:02,640 --> 00:20:04,120
Just like an ordinary flat space,

529
00:20:04,480 --> 00:20:06,840
the Cartesian coordinates are not unique

530
00:20:06,840 --> 00:20:08,380
because you can always rotate them.

531
00:20:08,540 --> 00:20:10,740
You can also rotate the best coordinates

532
00:20:10,740 --> 00:20:12,560
at a point.

533
00:20:13,020 --> 00:20:14,560
And that's not important.

534
00:20:14,700 --> 00:20:15,380
That won't change

535
00:20:15,380 --> 00:20:17,660
whether your vector stays parallel to itself.

536
00:20:18,400 --> 00:20:18,800
All right.

537
00:20:20,260 --> 00:20:23,740
Moving a vector from one point to another

538
00:20:25,199 --> 00:20:29,280
such that this covariant differential change

539
00:20:29,280 --> 00:20:33,760
is zero is called parallel transport of the vector.

540
00:20:34,920 --> 00:20:37,520
If you move a vector along a curve

541
00:20:39,010 --> 00:20:42,840
in such a way that the differential change

542
00:20:42,840 --> 00:20:45,480
in its contravariant component

543
00:20:46,280 --> 00:20:50,600
plus the Christoffel symbol multiplying v times dx

544
00:20:50,600 --> 00:20:51,920
along that trajectory,

545
00:20:52,840 --> 00:20:54,860
that being zero,

546
00:20:55,060 --> 00:20:56,440
is called

547
00:20:58,060 --> 00:21:01,040
parallelly transporting a vector along a certain curve.

548
00:21:02,060 --> 00:21:02,620
Now,

549
00:21:02,620 --> 00:21:04,960
the funny thing about curved spaces

550
00:21:04,960 --> 00:21:07,200
is if you take two points

551
00:21:08,120 --> 00:21:10,280
and you start a vector over here

552
00:21:10,280 --> 00:21:13,440
and parallelly transport it along this curve here,

553
00:21:13,540 --> 00:21:14,660
you'll get some other vector here.

554
00:21:15,220 --> 00:21:17,060
But if you choose some other curve

555
00:21:17,900 --> 00:21:19,840
and parallelly transport it,

556
00:21:19,920 --> 00:21:20,900
in general,

557
00:21:20,900 --> 00:21:21,760
it will come out different.

558
00:21:23,780 --> 00:21:26,420
So the notion of parallel transport

559
00:21:26,440 --> 00:21:30,160
is relative to a particular curve.

560
00:21:31,700 --> 00:21:33,540
This is what I showed you about cones.

561
00:21:34,180 --> 00:21:35,980
When we talked about having a cone

562
00:21:35,980 --> 00:21:37,860
with a round top or something like that,

563
00:21:38,600 --> 00:21:43,100
if we parallelly transport a vector from here to here

564
00:21:43,100 --> 00:21:46,140
versus transporting it around the back of the cone,

565
00:21:46,340 --> 00:21:48,360
you will get a different final result.

566
00:21:49,580 --> 00:21:51,600
So parallelly transport...

567
00:21:52,640 --> 00:21:53,860
I've got one question.

568
00:21:54,060 --> 00:21:54,260
Yeah.

569
00:21:55,120 --> 00:21:55,640
That's...

570
00:21:55,640 --> 00:21:56,320
And of course,

571
00:21:56,440 --> 00:21:57,100
when that happens,

572
00:21:57,180 --> 00:21:59,380
it's because there's curvature in between.

573
00:22:01,879 --> 00:22:03,360
So I know I'm misunderstanding,

574
00:22:03,620 --> 00:22:05,340
but tell me where I'm wrong.

575
00:22:05,520 --> 00:22:06,380
I figured this V,

576
00:22:06,380 --> 00:22:07,220
this vector,

577
00:22:07,280 --> 00:22:08,120
is a vector field.

578
00:22:08,860 --> 00:22:09,300
Okay.

579
00:22:09,800 --> 00:22:11,720
What I said was for a vector field,

580
00:22:11,860 --> 00:22:14,120
but now just imagine that...

581
00:22:14,120 --> 00:22:16,520
You could imagine that there was a vector field,

582
00:22:16,620 --> 00:22:18,300
or you could just imagine that the vector field

583
00:22:18,300 --> 00:22:20,000
was only defined along the curve.

584
00:22:20,980 --> 00:22:21,660
In fact,

585
00:22:21,660 --> 00:22:22,620
we don't even have to...

